05756nam a22008775i 9781501742415DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20192019nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2019020851  a97815017424157 a10.1515/97815017424152doi  a(DE-B1597)527361  a(OCoLC)1099539476  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY00aD804.348 4aD804.348b.S83 2020 7aHIS0430002bisacsh04a940.5318609472231 aSubotić, Jelena, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aYellow Star, Red Star :bHolocaust Remembrance after Communism /cJelena Subotić. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2019] 4c©2019  a1 online resource (264 p.) :b8 b&w halftones, 3 maps  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tPreface and Acknowledgments -- tAbbreviations -- tThe Big Gray Truck -- t1. The Politics of Holocaust Remembrance after Communism -- t2. At the Belgrade Fairgrounds -- t3. Croatia’s Islands of Memory -- t4. The Long Shadows of Vilna -- tThe Stakes of Holocaust Remembrance in the Twenty-First Century -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aYellow Star, Red Star asks why Holocaust memory continues to be so deeply troubled—ignored, appropriated, and obfuscated—throughout Eastern Europe, even though it was in those lands that most of the extermination campaign occurred. As part of accession to the European Union, Jelena Subotić shows, East European states were required to adopt, participate in, and contribute to the established Western narrative of the Holocaust. This requirement created anxiety and resentment in post-communist states: Holocaust memory replaced communist terror as the dominant narrative in Eastern Europe, focusing instead on predominantly Jewish suffering in World War II. Influencing the European Union's own memory politics and legislation in the process, post-communist states have attempted to reconcile these two memories by pursuing new strategies of Holocaust remembrance. The memory, symbols, and imagery of the Holocaust have been appropriated to represent crimes of communism.Yellow Star, Red Star presents in-depth accounts of Holocaust remembrance practices in Serbia, Croatia, and Lithuania, and extends the discussion to other East European states. The book demonstrates how countries of the region used Holocaust remembrance as a political strategy to resolve their contemporary "ontological insecurities"—insecurities about their identities, about their international status, and about their relationships with other international actors. As Subotić concludes, Holocaust memory in Eastern Europe has never been about the Holocaust or about the desire to remember the past, whether during communism or in its aftermath. Rather, it has been about managing national identities in a precarious and uncertain world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aHolocaust, Jewish (1939-1945)xAnniversaries, etc. 0aHolocaust, Jewish (1939-1945)zEurope, EasternxHistoriography. 0aHolocaust, Jewish (1939-1945)zEurope, EasternxInfluence. 0aMemorializationxPolitical aspectszEurope, Eastern. 0aNationalism and collective memoryzEurope, Eastern. 0aPost-communismzEurope, Eastern. 4aHistory. 4aJewish Studies. 4aWest European History. 7aHISTORY / Holocaust.2bisacsh  aHolocaust, East European politics, East European history, Jewish history, memorialization.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311065198008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019 Englishz978311061076508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019z9783110664232oZDB-23-DGG08